		<profileDesc>
			<abstract>
				<p>Information theory is used to derive a simple formula for the amount of information conveyed by the firing rate of a neuron about any experimentally measured variable or combination of variables (e.g. running speed, head direction, location of the animal, etc.). The derivation treats the cell as a communication channel whose input is the measured variable and whose output is the cell&apos;s spike train. Applying the formula, we find systematic differences in the information content of hippocampal &quot;place cells&quot; in different experimental conditions.</p>
			</abstract>
